I excelled in certain subjects and learned that I wanted to use those skills in my life. For example, I learned that I loved writing. 
I also learned that I didn't want to go to college.
 Rather than going to college, I just decided to do write in my spare time. I've used it in many different areas of my life and that has worked out for me. I think that school really is just a journey of figuring out what personally works for you. 

Some people will have the opposite experience and will learn that they have a love for learning. They want to continue to pursue learning and will go to college. For them, that is the best choice and makes them the happiest.

In my opinion, the most important thing that you can learn from school is how you respond to the experience. Everyone's perception is different and each person takes something different away from the experience. I learned personally that school wasn't for me. I excelled in certain subjects and learned that I wanted to use those skills in my life. For example, I learned that I loved writing. 
I also learned that I didn't want to go to college.
 Rather than going to college, I just decided to do write in my spare time. I've used it in many different areas of my life and that has worked out for me. I think that school really is just a journey of figuring out what personally works for you. 

Some people will have the opposite experience and will learn that they have a love for learning. They want to continue to pursue learning and will go to college. For them, that is the best choice and makes them the happiest.

Everyone's perception is different and each person takes something different away from the experience. I learned personally that school wasn't for me. I excelled in certain subjects and learned that I wanted to use those skills in my life. For example, I learned that I loved writing. 
I also learned that I didn't want to go to college.
 Rather than going to college, I just decided to do write in my spare time. I've used it in many different areas of my life and that has worked out for me. I think that school really is just a journey of figuring out what personally works for you.

Everyone's perception is different and each person takes something different away from the experience. I learned personally that school wasn't for me. I excelled in certain subjects and learned that I wanted to use those skills in my life. For example, I learned that I loved writing. 
I also learned that I didn't want to go to college.
 Rather than going to college, I just decided to do write in my spare time. I've used it in many different areas of my life and that has worked out for me. I think that school really is just a journey of figuring out what personally works for you.

Everyone's perception is different and each person takes something different away from the experience. I learned personally that school wasn't for me. I excelled in certain subjects and learned that I wanted to use those skills in my life. For example, I learned that I loved writing. 
I also learned that I didn't want to go to college.
 Rather than going to college, I just decided to do write in my spare time. I've used it in many different areas of my life and that has worked out for me. I think that school really is just a journey of figuring out what personally works for you. 

Some people will have the opposite experience and will learn that they have a love for learning. They want to continue to pursue learning and will go to college. For them, that is the best choice and makes them the happiest.

---

In my opinion, the most important thing that you can learn from school is how you respond to the experience. Everyone's perception is different and each person takes something different away from the experience. I learned personally that school wasn't for me. I excelled in certain subjects and learned that I wanted to use those skills in my life. For example, I learned that I loved writing. 
I also learned that I didn't want to go to college.
 Rather than going to college, I just decided to do write in my spare time. I've used it in many different areas of my life and that has worked out for me. I think that school really is just a journey of figuring out what personally works for you. 

Some people will have the opposite experience and will learn that they have a love for learning. They want to continue to pursue learning and will go to college. For them, that is the best choice and makes them the happiest. 

There is no set thing that one student should learn in school. The basics are already covered so you will know the basics to succeed in life by the time you leave high school. Everyone's perception is different and each person takes something different away from the experience. I learned personally that school wasn't for me. I excelled in certain subjects and learned that I wanted to use those skills in my life. For example, I learned that I loved writing. 
I also learned that I didn't want to go to college.
 Rather than going to college, I just decided to do write in my spare time. I've used it in many different areas of my life and that has worked out for me. I think that school really is just a journey of figuring out what personally works for you. 

Some people will have the opposite experience and will learn that they have a love for learning. They want to continue to pursue learning and will go to college. For them, that is the best choice and makes them the happiest.

Everyone's perception is different and each person takes something different away from the experience. I learned personally that school wasn't for me. I excelled in certain subjects and learned that I wanted to use those skills in my life. For example, I learned that I loved writing. 
I also learned that I didn't want to go to college.
 Rather than going to college, I just decided to do write in my spare time. I've used it in many different areas of my life and that has worked out for me. I think that school really is just a journey of figuring out what personally works for you. 

Some people will have the opposite experience and will learn that they have a love for learning. They want to continue to pursue learning and will go to college. For them, that is the best choice and makes them the happiest. 

There is no set thing that one student should learn in school. The basics are already covered so you will know the basics to succeed in life by the time you leave high school. What really is unique to each student is where you want to go from there. That's why students need to just spend time trying to figure out if they like structured learning or if they want to be more of free spirits and pursue things on their own.

Everyone's perception is different and each person takes something different away from the experience. I learned personally that school wasn't for me. I excelled in certain subjects and learned that I wanted to use those skills in my life. For example, I learned that I loved writing. 
I also learned that I didn't want to go to college.
 Rather than going to college, I just decided to do write in my spare time. I've used it in many different areas of my life and that has worked out for me. I think that school really is just a journey of figuring out what personally works for you. 

Some people will have the opposite experience and will learn that they have a love for learning. They want to continue to pursue learning and will go to college. For them, that is the best choice and makes them the happiest. 

There is no set thing that one student should learn in school. The basics are already covered so you will know the basics to succeed in life by the time you leave high school. What really is unique to each student is where you want to go from there. That's why students need to just spend time trying to figure out if they like structured learning or if they want to be more of free spirits and pursue things on their own. 

What really ends up mattering is if students are happy with their decision. Their experiences should guide them to finding out who they really are. People

Everyone's perception is different and each person takes something different away from the experience. I learned personally that school wasn't for me. I excelled in certain subjects and learned that I wanted to use those skills in my life. For example, I learned that I loved writing. 
I also learned that I didn't want to go to college.
 Rather than going to college, I just decided to do write in my spare time. I've used it in many different areas of my life and that has worked out for me. I think that school really is just a journey of figuring out what personally works for you. 

Some people will have the opposite experience and will learn that they have a love for learning. They want to continue to pursue learning and will go to college. For them, that is the best choice and makes them the happiest. 

There is no set thing that one student should learn in school. The basics are already covered so you will know the basics to succeed in life by the time you leave high school. What really is unique to each student is where you want to go from there. That's why students need to just spend time trying to figure out if they like structured learning or if they want to be more of free spirits and pursue things on their own. 

What really ends up mattering is if students are happy with their decision. Their experiences should guide them to finding out who they really are. People often say that college is where you find yourself, but I do not think that is correct. College is where certain people find themselves. Oth

I excelled in certain subjects and learned that I wanted to use those skills in my life. For example, I learned that I loved writing. 
I also learned that I didn't want to go to college.
 Rather than going to college, I just decided to do write in my spare time. I've used it in many different areas of my life and that has worked out for me. I think that school really is just a journey of figuring out what personally works for you. 

Some people will have the opposite experience and will learn that they have a love for learning. They want to continue to pursue learning and will go to college. For them, that is the best choice and makes them the happiest. 

There is no set thing that one student should learn in school. The basics are already covered so you will know the basics to succeed in life by the time you leave high school. What really is unique to each student is where you want to go from there. That's why students need to just spend time trying to figure out if they like structured learning or if they want to be more of free spirits and pursue things on their own. 

What really ends up mattering is if students are happy with their decision. Their experiences should guide them to finding out who they really are. I excelled in certain subjects and learned that I wanted to use those skills in my life. For example, I learned that I loved writing. 
I also learned that I didn't want to go to college.
 Rather than going to college, I just decided to do write in my spare time. I've used it in many different areas of my life and that has worked out for me. I think that school really is just a journey of figuring out what personally works for you. 

Some people will have the opposite experience and will learn that they have a love for learning. They want to continue to pursue learning and will go to college. For them, that is the best choice and makes them the happiest. 

There is no set thing that one student should learn in school. The basics are already covered so you will know the basics to succeed in life by the time you leave high school. What really is unique to each student is where you want to go from there. That's why students need to just spend time trying to figure out if they like structured learning or if they want to be more of free spirits and pursue things on their own. 

What really ends up mattering is if students are happy with their decision. Their experiences should guide them to finding out who they really are. Everyone's perception is different and each person takes something different away from the experience. I learned personally that school wasn't for me. I excelled in certain subjects and learned that I wanted to use those skills in my life. For example, I learned that I loved writing. 
I also learned that I didn't want to go to college.
 Rather than going to college, I just decided to do write in my spare time. I've used it in many different areas of my life and that has worked out for me. I think that school really is just a journey of figuring out what personally works for you. 

Some people will have the opposite experience and will learn that they have a love for learning. They want to continue to pursue learning and will go to college. For them, that is the best choice and makes them the happiest. 

There is no set thing that one student should learn in school. The basics are already covered so you will know the basics to succeed in life by the time you leave high school. What really is unique to each student is where you want to go from there. That's why students need to just spend time trying to figure out if they like structured learning or if they want to be more of free spirits and pursue things on their own. 

What really ends up mattering is if students are happy with their decision. Their experiences should guide them to finding out who they really are. People often say that college is where you find yourself, but I do not think that is correct. College is where certain people find themselves. ---

In my opinion, the most important thing that you can learn from school is how you respond to the experience. Everyone's perception is different and each person takes something different away from the experience. I learned personally that school wasn't for me. I excelled in certain subjects and learned that I wanted to use those skills in my life. For example, I learned that I loved writing. 
I also learned that I didn't want to go to college.
 Rather than going to college, I just decided to do write in my spare time. I've used it in many different areas of my life and that has worked out for me. I think that school really is just a journey of figuring out what personally works for you. 

Some people will have the opposite experience and will learn that they have a love for learning. They want to continue to pursue learning and will go to college. For them, that is the best choice and makes them the happiest. 

There is no set thing that one student should learn in school. The basics are already covered so you will know the basics to succeed in life by the time you leave high school. What really is unique to each student is where you want to go from there. That's why students need to just spend time trying to figure out if they like structured learning or if they want to be more of free spirits and pursue things on their own. 

What really ends up mattering is if students are happy with their decision. Their experiences should guide them to finding out who they really are. People often say that college is where you find yourself, but I do not think that is correct. College is where certain people find themselves. Other people who decided not to go already know that a different path is for them and are finding themselves in an entirely different way. No one way is correct, it all just comes down to finding your own path in life.
